Lung Weights

Loading Data

#Load demographic data for gender
demo <- read_excel("~/Documents/ROCIanalysis/ROCI_101918.xlsx", sheet = "Outcomes", range = cell_cols(1:4), col_types = c("numeric", "skip", "skip", "numeric"))

#Load imaging/weight data and merge
weights <- read_excel("~/Documents/ROCIanalysis/ROCI_101918.xlsx", sheet = "LungWt", range = cell_cols(1:12)) %>% 
  gather(side, weight, r_lung_wt:l_lung_wt) %>%
  mutate(side = ifelse(side == "r_lung_wt", "right", "left"), side_total = ifelse(side == "right", quad1+quad3, quad2+quad4)) %>%
  filter(wi_24h == 1) %>%
  left_join(., demo, by = "Subject_ID") %>% 
  mutate(Male = as.factor(Male))

Analysis

Summary Statistics

Our lungs appear to be slightly heavier than those included in the RALE sample.

summ <- weights %>% summarise(mean = mean(weight, na.rm=T), median = median(weight, na.rm=T)) 
summ
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##    mean median
##   <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  938.    910

Testing for normality

The data are non-normal.

shapiro.test(weights$weight)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  weights$weight
## W = 0.92041, p-value = 9.412e-06
weights %>% ggplot(aes(weight)) + geom_histogram()

Spearman

Our Spearman is much lower than that reported in the RALE study. They reported rho = 0.59 for all explants and rho = 0.73 for the heavy subset.

cor.test(weights$side_total, weights$weight, method = "spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  weights$side_total and weights$weight
## S = 149200, p-value = 0.02008
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.2266304
rale_weights <- weights %>% filter(weight > 910)  #spearman on those greater than the median
cor.test(rale_weights$side_total, rale_weights$weight, method = "spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  rale_weights$side_total and rale_weights$weight
## S = 16465, p-value = 0.0324
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.2971655

Linear regression

Based on the residual diagnostics, it is reasonable to use linear regression despite the data being non-normal (below). This allows us to control for the confounders of height and gender on lung weight.

weights %>% ggplot(aes(side_total, weight, color = side)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

wt <- lm(weight ~ side_total+height+Male, data = weights)
summary(wt)
